This Is What Will Happen When the Federal Reserve Raises the Interest Rate
Interest rates will rise and the bull market will stumble, bond yields will rise and the economy will go into recession.
That we know.
What we do not know is how long it will happen and how long it will last.
In economics, history offers little clue about framing over time.
After the first rate hike, the recession occurred in just 11 months and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness to raise interest rates is often, though not always, a determining factor in how the economy and financial assets respond.
That’s why U.S. central bank officials have stressed so strongly that investors should not focus on when interest rates start to rise, but on the trajectory of the time it takes for normalization.
There are many variables in the game.
But in the end, market players may find that all the unrest associated with the rise in interest rates has been exaggerated.
“The first interest rate hike decided by the Fed after the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some voices as a sign of the ‘cheap money’ era,” said Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, in a note addressed to customers.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to more normal but still low levels to be the seismic shock everyone seems to fear.
However, it cannot be said that there will be no effect.
Below we present how several sectors of the economy could react, based on historical trends:
Given the situation the market has faced in recent months, anticipating the rise of interest rates can volatile things for a while.
However, at the time of growth, the impact is not so dramatic.
"There seems to be a tendency for capital yields to stagnate for 12-24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the fault in monetary policy," Deutsche Bank analysts said in a recent study of what will happen after the Fed's gains.
Specifically, over the past 35 years, the market has grown abruptly – by approximately 14 percent – moving towards the interest rate rise, quite invariant in the 250-day period after (average rise of 2.6 percent) and then returning to normal after 500 days, with an average return in the last six cycles of 14.4 percent, according to a recent analysis published on Barron by Nuveen Asset Management’s chief strategist.
Deutsche said the impact on stocks tends to become more pronounced later in the interest rate rise cycle and the benefits begin to decline.
Recession is a reality of economic life but rising interest rates often contribute to it.
In this situation, the Fed is facing conditions that did not exist before and that could accelerate a recession.
More specifically, the gross domestic product will approach its historic low for an increase in the Fed interest rate.
According to Deutsche Bank, of the 118 interest rate increases since 1950, only twice the nominal GDP was below 4.5%.
Although in the second quarter of 2015 the figure was 3.6%, few expect the situation to persist, the third quarter reaching only 1.5%, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Rising interest rates in such a fragile economy could be risky and could raise the question “if this time is different,” Deutsche said.
Market players have been preparing for a growth decision from the Fed all year round, with all eyes on this week’s meeting of the Federal Open Market Commission, which ends on Thursday.
Although many strategists and economists are of the opinion that the FOMC could approve an increase in interest rates at this meeting, futures trades indicate a probability of only 25%.
“In our study since 1950, all interest rate growth cycles so far have been in a super profit growth cycle, with GDP overshadowing pre-recession peaks very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
On the contrary, this was a strangely slow recovery after the worst recession in the period considered.
The current cycle is by far the longest expected by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and it reached 74 months and continues.
Fixed income has also been volatile given that the market anticipates an increase in interest rates and the pattern is somewhat similar to that of dividends.
The main difference is that the impact is faster for bonds than for stocks when the Fed changes policy.
In the case of bonds, it seems that the benefits change direction as soon as the first rise/fall in the cycle occurs.
At the end of the interest rate rise cycle, the yield of bonds immediately drops,” Deutsche said.
Strategists Charles Schwab are of the opinion that these interest rate increases will lead to the approximation of short-term and long-term bond yields, flattening the curve.
High yield bonds do better in such an environment, although “we’re still cautious about forcing yields,” said Kathy Jones, a fixed-income analyst at Schwab.
Interestingly, Jones is of the opinion that the markets have already adapted to the expectations of the Fed’s policy.
“In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in estimated inflation, there are some signs that the market has adapted to the prospect of a stricter monetary policy,” Jones wrote.
Short-term interest rates have risen, the yield curve is more straight, the average loan rate spread has expanded and volatility has increased – all characteristics of the market when the Fed is tightening the policy.
In general, companies that operate mostly in the U.S. will benefit from rising interest rates and local products will become more attractive.
High-debted multinationals will suffer because the rise of the dollar will drive their products up in the global market space and their debt will be more expensive.
“History shows that ‘quality’ stocks tend to be more profitable in the three months following an initial interest rate rise,” Goldman Sachs said in a customer report.
Firms with strong balance sheets surpassed those with a weak balance sheet after each of the interest rate increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004 by an average of 5 percentage points.
Companies with high capital gains and low volatility stocks also outperformed similar companies of lower quality by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points).
Debt will become an important issue.
Companies with a high percentage of floating debt have the most to lose, Goldman says.
Consumers will also benefit from the rise of the dollar.
Those who save might also have to profit, although experts do not agree on how quickly this will happen.
