Advantages and Disadvantages of Credit Conversion in Swiss Francs
On the banking market have already appeared two offers to convert loans in Swiss francs, the main advantages being the exclusion of foreign exchange risk and the reduction of rates.
Disadvantages can come over a few years, when variable interest rates can lead to higher rates.
Bank Transylvania has just completed the process of converting Volksbank loans into francs, and Bancpost has announced a conversion offer for its own clients.
According to data collected by analysts of the financial portal FinZoom, Bancpost offers three years of fixed interest rate at RON, of 1.5%, the lowest on the market.
On the other hand, Bank Transilvania’s conversion offer was accepted by 83% of clients with francs credit due to two successive discounts: the balance was reduced with the value of the risk and administration fees paid by the client, then an additional reduction of 22.5% was applied to the RON balance.
Both offers reduce the rates of their own customers, compared to how much they paid monthly equivalent in RON before the conversion.
Thus, the Bank of Transylvania reduced the rate by 42.5%, and Bancpost, by 33% in the first three years and, in theory, by 18% in the following years.
Benefits
The main advantage of the CHF credit coverage is that it eliminates foreign exchange risk, the consumer is protected from future increases in the franc, and the repayment of the credit will be made in the currency in which he receives his salary.
Another major advantage of both conversion offers is that there is no re-evaluation of the property, no additional guarantees and another proof of income are required.
Basically, there will be no new financial and legal analysis of the loan and there will be no additional costs as in the case of a refinancing.
Both banks also offer a discount on the monthly rate, compared to what customers paid before the conversion, equivalent in RON.
Risked
The problem is that the rate in the first years is made up more of interest, and the customer pays back very little of the principal.
Bancpost’s very low interest rate offer in the first three years appears to be advantageous for customers.
It is unclear how this will evolve in three years.
The margin offered to customers can be greater than 3.25%, so overall, and the cost reduction is lower.
A possible risk for all loans in variable interest rates is that the ROBOR index will increase significantly in the coming years (more than the Libor index - CHF).
For example, ROBOR at three months is now 1.44%, but in 2013 it had reached the value of 6%, in 2009, to over 15%, and in a few days in 2008 it exceeded 40%!
In addition, other costs may arise, not mentioned in the initial offer.
