Production and agriculture come to the service of supermarkets, as was the case in France.
The same thing happens with music, the same logic.
Les Dissonances makes reds maybe not too beautiful, but when we cut them, they are real reds.
In an ideal world, this music should return to the center and that the institutions and industries that manage this system understand that music does not need to be sold, but needs to be shared, and this can be done starting with education policy.
“If we considered – as the Koreans, Chinese, Japanese do – that Western music is one of the most beautiful things of humanity, we would reintroduce its learning in school, we would reintroduce television concerts and through this education we would no longer need to sell musical by-products,” Grimal says.
Certainly, there are things in classical music education that remain very communist, that everywhere is something very militarized.
It depends on this discipline whether we compare a musician to a soldier, or whether we form a musician who will sing to an instrument, being, above all, a musician.
We are talking about a completely different education, if we want to train a soldier (this education) must be in a way, if we want to train a musician, it is completely different.
In your opinion, what is more dangerous, a soldier or a musician?” asked the French artist, smiling.
Grimal points out that, for artists, the reward of a different way of making music comes precisely from overcoming this "soldier" status, overcoming what "they think is their limits": "Musicists discover at some point that they are not soldiers, and therefore after the concert they come out smiling."
David Grimal spoke about his musical project and his vision of music and the artist in the "Festival of Ideas", a discussion with the audience organized at the George Enescu International Festival by the Aspen Institute Romania.
