At the most anticipated meeting in recent years, Federal Reserve policymakers will spend two days this week around a 27-foot Honduran mahon table to decide whether it’s time to raise a key interest rate for the first time in a decade.
Above them, at one end of the central bank’s meeting room, a wall painting of the United States will be seen.
The map is meant to remind that Janet L. Yellen, President of the Fed, and her colleagues must put the economic interests of the nation above anything.
The Central Bank has been given a double task from Congress: to maximize U.S. employment rate and maintain price stability.
But since the Great Economic Crisis, the Fed leaders have confirmed that there is a third unwritten task: financial stability.
And this third task could be the X factor in a decision too hard to forecast, which will be announced on Tuesday, to determine whether the U.S. economy is ready to get rid of the unprecedented boost offered by the near-zero short-term interest rate in force since the end of 2008.
Even though most data indicate a strong-growing economy, recent turmoil in global financial markets could scare Fed officials already cautious about adding volatility by raising the federal fund reference rate — even by just a quarter-point.
“Of course, labour market and inflation will be the first and main aspects that will follow,” said Lindsey M. Piegza, chief economist at brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“But I think if they were looking for an excuse not to raise interest rates, the growing uncertainty in the global market would be enough to give them reason to wait,” she said.
There is no consensus on the decision the Fed will make, which itself creates instability in the financial markets.
About half of the economists recently polled by Bloomberg anticipated a rise in interest rates this week.
But financial markets are expecting the Fed to delay, a key indicator showing that the likelihood of growth is only 30 percent.
This would indicate a fall on the stock market if the Fed raises the interest rate, unless policy makers would mitigate the blow by promising that it would take a long time until the next increase.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4%, to 16.599.85.
The boost was triggered by expectations that Fed decision makers will keep interest rates stable this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It would be surprising if the Fed raised interest rates at this time,” Lonski said.
If the Fed’s decision makers did, “they should act in depth in their policies to avoid panic in the financial markets.”
Other experts said a rise in interest rates would soothe financial markets as it would remove the uncertainty about when the Fed will act.
Just a month ago, the Fed seemed to be about to raise the rate by 0.25% this month, the first small step towards slowly tightening monetary conditions that would confirm the strength of the U.S. recovery.
Yellen said in the spring and early summer that she expected interest rates to rise this year despite liberal objections that more economic progress would be needed.
Although job creation slowed in August, growth in the labour market has been solid this year.
The unemployment rate dropped to 5.1% last month, the lowest rate in more than seven years and close to the level considered by the Fed as total employment.
Wage gains showed signs of growth.
And while inflation continued to be below the central bank’s annual target, Fed decision makers said a key reason was the temporary effect of the sudden drop in oil prices.
The economy “can cope with higher rates and needs them given the tension in the labor market,” said Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
But global financial markets began to fibrillate at the end of this month after China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped 16 percent below its record high in May as investors feared a slowdown in the Chinese economy would drag down global growth.
The market fell slightly this month, with the Dow index now approximately 10% below its May peak.
For Fed decision makers, market agitation adds to the complex calculation of the moment to raise the interest rate.
“Without what has happened to the financial markets and the news of China’s weakening economy in recent weeks, it would be stronger at the meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, an experienced researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and former Fed official.
Now, he expects they will wait at least a month to better manage the effects.
“There is a lot of uncertainty about what the impact will be on the U.S. economy, and they have almost no data on which to rely after events in China,” Oliner said.
The well-being of the global economy is not one of the Fed’s major interests, so it should virtually not be taken into account in decision-making.
But in reality, the Fed has become the global monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the central bank has been huge.
The mere hint by then-president Ben S. Bernanke in 2013 that the Fed could “strengthen” its monetary expansion has triggered an earthquake in global markets.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly clogged, it is expected that Fed officials will not only monitor progress in other areas, but also consult with other central banks and experts to better interpret the global economy.
His decision-making is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, head of global strategy at Envestnet.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Va., said this month that “The Fed has a history of overdimensional reaction to changes in the financial market that appear to be unrelated to economic bases.”
Lacker, a voting member of the Federal Open Market Commission, a decision-making body that advocated an increase in interest rates, gave the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
A financial crisis that hit Asia has prompted the Fed to lower the benchmark rate by 0.75% in three meetings, “despite the limited identification implications for U.S. development,” Lacker said.
A year later, the Fed officials reverted to those cuts.
The Fed should only put the issue of financial stability first in the event of a major crisis, such as the 2008 market earthquake, said Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The last turbulent period is not far from that level, he said.
“We don’t want to get into the situation of fearing a rise in interest rates because the markets are upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still holds the double mandate and does not mention financial stability and, until anything changes in that regard, I don’t think it should take early action.
