Weight reduction surgery could be useful for diabetics with mild obesity
The benefits of weight reduction surgery in people with mild obesity with type 2 diabetes could beined for at least five years, according to a new study.
It is still premature to say whether diabetics with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those who follow non-surgical treatments.
“It takes a long time to centralize mortality data,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, a specialist in obesity surgery, as she wrote an article on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss operations, also called bariatric surgery, use various methods to shrink the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proven to be effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a unit of measurement of weight relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18,5-24,9.
A BMI of at least 25 indicates that a person is overweight and people with a BMI above 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI by visiting: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers at Taiwan’s Min-Sheng General Hospital used data gathered after 2007 in a trial that compared two types of bariatric surgery – gastric bypass and mansion gastrectomy – in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The average BMI in people who underwent surgery dropped from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year of the study.
Meanwhile, the BMI in people who received non-surgical treatments against diabetes remained almost at the same level, namely 29.
Of those who underwent surgery, diabetes was completely cured in 36% and partially in 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partially in only 2% of subjects.
In addition, blood pressure control, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
The researchers also monitored blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood glucose levels over time.
The researchers write that the optimal level of hemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
After surgery, the average level of hemoglobin A1c dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
But in the group treated by medical methods, it remained at around 8%.
But this improved “glycemic control” – reflected by improved hemoglobin A1c levels – did not reduce the mortality rate to five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared to the group with handcuff gastrectomy, the group with bypass surgery lost more weight (18.7 versus 14.2 kg), experienced more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 versus 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% versus 2.1%) and had a higher likelihood of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% versus 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate any benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on overweight individuals in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, of the University of Arizona, School of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery had an approximately 29% lower likelihood of dying after 15 years compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a survival benefit in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it is an optimistic outlook for people with BMI under 35 interested in the procedure.
“This is the point where this paper is critical because it states that this surgery is safe in the group with lower BMI,” without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease, she says.
Blackstone added that patients and their doctors should start taking weight seriously when the patient’s BMI reaches 27-30.
“I think we’re waiting too long to urge people to take this issue seriously,” she said.
I think once they have accumulated these genetic changes that have shortened their bodies predisposing them to obesity and diabetes, it is extremely difficult to get back to normal.
