The number of children who have ingested hand detergent in the last four years has quadrupled.
According to the Georgia Anti-Poisoning Center, U.S. anti-poisoning centers have an increase of about 400% since 2010 in the number of children under the age of 12 who swallowed high-alcohol hand detergent.
According to Dr. Gaylord Lopez, director of the Georgia Anti-Poisoning Center, cases of hand detergent ingestion in children under 12 years of age at anti-poisoning centers rose from 3,266 in 2010 to 16,117 in 2014.
“Children have more access to these products and unfortunately a percentage of them go to the emergency room,” Lopez told CNN.
Lopez said some children deliberately drink detergent while others do so to impress their friends or respond to challenges on social media.
You can watch videos on YouTube that show teenagers how to drink detergent to create cheap drinks.
It turns out that teenagers mixed the detergent with mouthwater with alcohol to get a stronger drink.
Younger children may be attracted to the attractive smell of the detergent.
“A child doesn’t think it’s hurting them,” says Lopez.
Many of the most attractive types (hand detergent) are fragrances.
Hand detergents with the aroma of strawberries, grapes, orange are the most attractive for children.
Hand detergent contains approximately 45-95% alcohol.
Especially in young children, just a few swallows can cause alcohol poisoning.
“It’s very concentrated alcohol,” Dr. Stephen Thornton, medical director of the anti-poisoning center at Kansas University Hospital, told Fox Channel 4 in Kansas City.
Thus, we avoid leaving a glass of whiskey on the table, but people leave these hand detergents in accessible places and if the little ones get to them, this is a quick way to consume a lot of alcohol.
Nhaijah Russell, a six-year-old girl who recently ingested the equivalent of four stoves of strawberry-aromated hand detergent at school, arrived at the emergency room to receive treatment.
She had alcoholemia179, twice the threshold at which an adult is considered by law under the influence of alcohol, according to Dr. Chris Ritchey, an emergency room doctor who treated her at Gwinnett Medical Center outside Atlanta.
Nhaijah was stunned and could not walk when he arrived at the emergency room.
Doctors monitored her overnight in a separate children's hospital to identify signs of brain injury as she fell and hit herself in the head because of alcohol, Ritchey said.
“It was terrifying,” Ortoria Scott, Nhaijah’s mother, told CNN.
It could have been fatal.
Lopez advised parents and teachers to use alcohol-free wet products or towels and to stop leaving the hand detergent out of children’s reach.
In addition to alcohol poisoning, some detergents have been associated with deaths.
In 2013, two women in Ontario died after swallowing a hand detergent containing a toxic, undeclared ingredient.
Health authorities assumed that the product contained methanol, a lethal substance, and not ethyl alcohol, specified as the active ingredient.
In January, three fourth grade students in northern New York plotted to poison their “bad” teacher “by putting antibacterial products in the classroom,” according to a police report.
The teacher is very allergic to hand detergent and has banned it in her classroom.
The police considered the plan “insignificant” and referred the disciplinary matter to the school inspectorate.
