The government approved on Wednesday the "National Immigration Strategy for the period 2015-2018" and the "Action Plan for the current year", documents considered to be "another stage that Romania is going through as part of the efforts to modernize the immigration management process on the national territory", according to a press release.
The strategy aims to effectively manage the immigration phenomenon, including general strategic objectives, specific objectives and directions of action that reflect the policies established at European level, adapted to national realities.
In view of the problems faced by the States in the immediate neighbourhood of Romania, measures are considered for the unitary and coherent management of situations determined by the possible appearance of an influx of illegal immigrants into the territory of Romania, generated by situations of crisis of a political, social, economic or military nature.
“The Romanian authorities will contribute to the creation of a flexible admission system, but at the same time will pay special attention to citizens coming from countries with a potential migrationist or that may harm national security,” the source added.
The strategy identifies a number of factors that can influence immigration and asylum, includingining the conflict situation in Syria, reactivating the conflict in Iraq,ining an unstable situation in the areas bordering Romania (Ukraine, Transnistria), perpetuating and increasing intensity of the Israeli-Palestinian armed conflict.
On the other hand, the document also sets a number of general strategic objectives related to immigration, such as: promoting legal migration, stricter controls of the legality of third-country nationals’ stay on the Romanian territory and the appropriate application of removal and restrictive measures, improvement of the national asylum system.
The national strategy shall also include specific objectives relevant to the transposition and implementation of the general strategic objectives.
These include: facilitating access to the Romanian territory of third-party nationals who meet the needs of employment, favouring access of third-party nationals to higher education institutions in Romania for the fields and professions identified as deficient.
Regarding the 2015 Action Plan, the Government appreciates that it represents “a means by which concrete activities are established that will lead to the creation of a flexible system for stopping the growing migrationist phenomenon”.
Romania at the top of the European labour market
Latvia, Romania and Bulgaria recorded the highest increase in total labor costs among EU member states in the second quarter of the year, compared to the same period in 2014, according to data published on Wednesday by the European Statistical Office (Eurostat).
The index refers to the employee expenses of employers.
Between April and June 2015, the total cost of labour rose by 1.9% in the European Union and by 1.6% in the euro area.
Romania, third in the EU in the increase in labour cost
The highest increases were in Latvia (7.9%), Romania (7.7%), Bulgaria (6.8%), Estonia (5,5%) and Lithuania (4.3%).
The only EU countries where the hourly cost of labour decreased in the second quarter of this year were Greece (minus 2.9%), Cyprus (minus 1.2%) and Italy (minus 0.4%).
The increase in labor costs in Romania between April and June 2015 is mainly due to the increase in hourly labor costs in industry and services, by 7.9% and 7.6%, respectively.
In the construction sector, Romania recorded an increase of 5.8% of the hourly cost of labour.
