What button will appear soon?
Millions of Facebook users have become accustomed to the "Like" button, and now the representatives of the social network are preparing another opposite, the "Dislike".
Mark Zuckerberg, co-founder and chief executive officer of the company, announced on his account that this button will be available soon, the New York Times reports on its blog.
Zuckerberg said the “Dislike” button would show a shade of what a user feels rather than a mere option.
However, his ad raised the problem that Facebook could become a less friendly place.
Zuckerberg said he wants to avoid the times when someone posts on his account or an important event in life, and someone else will give "dislike".
Users of the network, which has reached 1.5 billion active accounts, have long sought the opportunity to express their negative emotions or empathy with something sad.
Mark Zuckerberg said it is not very comfortable for people to like current events, such as the refugee crisis, or the death of a family member.
“You may not feel comfortable giving like to that post,” the Facebook spokesman said.
The new version of the Facebook button was not well received by everyone.
“There is already enough hatred on Facebook and on social media,” said Atiq Haneef of Afghanistan on the Facebook page of the New York Times, where the article was posted.
“I’ll give ‘Dislike’ to the ‘Dislike’ button,” he said.
Roger Anderson, a microbiologist from Atlanta, argued that there is nothing wrong with this button, encouraging people to have different opinions on Facebook.
Debra Aho Williamson, a social media analyst at eMarketer, said it’s hard to imagine that a single button can convey a complex range of negative emotions.
Moreover, she argues, the election campaign in America is approaching, and the "Dislike" button would create a total disaster.
