At the age of 20 she received a gift from her biological parents.
Lost in the hospital under unclear conditions, in the darkness of the 1990s, when she was only two months old, small, sick and helpless, and then adopted by a wealthy family from Italy, in the same years in which adoption was vaguely regulated, a young outgoing girl, now a blonde and beautiful girl, met yesterday in Iasi with her biological parents from a county village, after almost two decades in which no one knew anything about the others.
Crina will be 20 years old these days, and her adoptive parents from Palermo have thought to give their beloved daughter a stunning and courageous gift: a visit to Romania, Iasi, to know their unclear past.
The "Iasi newspaper", which witnessed the search efforts of the home family after a few extremely vague clues, witnessed these encounters that practically break your heart.
The reporting of reporters, the emotions of the moments, the statements of those involved, their reactions are quite moving and overwhelming.
The story of Crina began 20 years ago in the outgoing village of Ruginoasa, when she was only two months old.
Then, due to a health problem, the girl had to be admitted to the hospital in the city.
At home, there began to be disagreements between the parents, and the mother had to leave the home.
He decided to keep the girl and send me out of the house.
He stopped the girl, and since then I have not known anything.
“When I found out she was in the hospital, it was too late,” recalls Alina, the girl’s biological mother.
Crina was interned with her grandmother at the municipal hospital in Pascani, and also then her father, Costica Balcan, went to work in the city of Alexandria, Teleorman County.
Their lives were finally separated.
She has not been found in the hospital.
After being interned, Crina’s father went to work in another locality, and returned after six months.
Meanwhile, the girl was transferred to the Iasi hospital, and the father, when he returned, did not find her.
It was nine months since the girl was in the hospital.
“She thought she was abandoned,” one of the family’s grandchildren said.
Due to financial problems, the grandmother could not come with Crina to Iasi, and the girl remained in the care of doctors.
Since no one was interested in the fate of the child throughout this time, it was taken over by the Iasi General Directorate of Social Assistance and Child Protection, which then gave it to the care of the Placement Center in Bucium.
There were years when abandonment and adoption were more easily regulated than in Romania today.
At the Bucium Center she was found by the Italian Salvador and his wife, a couple from Palermo who wanted to have their child but failed.
They fell in love with the blonde Crina, and after a while she would move with them to Italy.
The little girl was almost two years old, as long as the adoption formalities lasted.
When we saw Crina, we felt like she was our girlfriend.
“It’s as if my wife gave him life,” says Salvadore, the adoptive father, smiling as he grabs the girl’s weak hand in his palm.
In the country, the parents of Crina, Alina and Costica, continued the search separately, each where they could.
The father asked the authorities in Ruginoasa, but he did not receive any answer where his child could be.
The police then told her that she may have died, but at Iasi the parents learned what really happened to their daughter.
When I searched for her here, they told me at the Tribunal that she had gone to Italy, to Palermo.
I had no conditions to look for it.
I prayed to God that he would be well.
I have been thinking about it all the years that have passed, but there were no possibilities for us to walk, to find it.
“It’s hard,” says Lina’s biological mother with tears in her eyes.
However, despite the years that passed, the parents of Ruginoasa were not forgotten.
In Italy, Salvadore and his wife explained to the girl where she came from and that her past connects her with Romania.
I was small when I found out.
I think I was five or six years old.
I reacted like a child, I was curious.
“I wanted to meet my parents in Romania,” Crina confesses delighted.
And her dream would become reality.
In March of this year, Chief Commissioner Romica Ichim, director of the Iasi Regional Centre for Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Counseling, was contacted by an Italian acquaintance who explained to him Salvador’s desire to find the biological family of Crina.
The search started with a name.
Following the request we had from our partners in Italy, we started the first steps.
We took only one name, the Coastal Balkans, and then the locality, Ruginoasa.
Soon I had an activity with the municipality there, and I could ask if there is by locality the name received.
Then they gave me some indications, only that the person found was not the one sought.
"It finally took about a month for us to find the girl's biological father," said Chief Commissioner Romica Ichim.
Overall, it took the authorities more than three months to find Costica and Alina, especially since each had a residence in a different locality.
We started somewhere in March, and in June-July we completed the identification of biological parents and discussions.
“Then we agreed that a first meeting would take place in September,” Romica Ichim added.
In the past weekend, Alina and Costica saw their daughter lost in the hallways of the Iasi hospital 20 years ago.
His father, excited, could hardly control his tears, and his hands kept trembling.
He barely exchanged a few words with others.
A week before the meeting, he could not even sleep.
He was excited, trembling.
"To see your child after so many years, is something," says a granddaughter, who also came with Costica from Ruginoasa.
Meeting with biological mother and brother
In talks with his daughter, who is going to study at a well-rated university in Italy, Costica Balcan told him, among other things, that if she wants to return to him, in the village, she should come quietly: she can give him some sheep, goats, so that she can find a boy from the village and build a household.
Her mother is also excited, she is crying, and she can hardly believe that something like this could happen to her.
I am very excited.
I did not think that something like this could happen.
I’ve seen such cases on television, I’ve been thinking about it all these years, I’ve hoped, but I didn’t think I could be like that.
They are very big emotions.
If he could forgive me.
I hope to visit in the future.
"I hope we can keep in touch," says Alina, the mother of Crina, with tears on her cheeks, while holding a towel tightly in her hand.
In it she still hides her tears of happiness, because soon she will see her girl after so much bitter time.
On the other hand, Crina, who will be just a few days old this month, 20 years old, tries to calm down like an emotional child.
She doesn’t know what to expect, but she has a vague idea about her biological parents.
He thinks they are young, but now before the meeting he tries to gather his thoughts, because he has a lot to say, but nothing to reproach.
My parents are two mothers and two fathers.
My parents were the ones who raised me.
It will be a wonderful meeting, a wonderful experience.
"I hope to have a nice memory with them, because now there are so many things to say," Crina confesses to us.
First Family Meeting in Iowa
In the Unirii Square, under the sky of the beginning of autumn, the Ruginoasa family once again unites their destiny with their daughter from Palermo.
Crina is now 20 years old, finishing high school, following the Italian school model, but can start a new chapter with Alina and Costica, her biological parents.
They are no longer separated by borders or countries, but only by a barrier: that of the language.
Over which, with the help of a translator, an Italian local owner in the centre of Iaș, passed easily.
Those who have managed to make this meeting possible say it is the first event of this kind, and that in the future, if the opportunity arises, they will do so again.
It is the first event of this kind organized, of such an emotional load, and I am pleased to be a success.
We, at the Center, have different activities, and most of the time we are associated as an institution that deals only with consumers, drug addicts.
But we are trying to give back something good to society.
"If I am asked for such an event again, I will do so with great love," says Romica Ichim, director of the Iasi Regional Center for Drug Prevention, Evaluation and Advisory.
Behind him, the Balcan family, with Crina in the middle, goes away telling stories.
They have a lot to say to each other.
