Brexit and the future of Europe
Because of economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity they have over the past decades can no longer continue the same way in the years to come.
Until Saturday, probably few people in Romania knew who Jeremy Corbyn was.
Even today, after he became the new leader of the UK Labour Party, many wonder how much it can affect us to choose a politician who, after all, is not in a decision-making position.
Jeremy Corbyn is the most radical leftist Labour leader since the end of the war.
A declared Marxist, anti-monarchist (he once asked Tony Blair, then prime minister, to take the royal family out of Buckingham Palace), a fierce anti-American and a sympathizer of Vladimir Putin (he was also regularly invited to comment on political events by the TV channel "Russia Today"), and of the terrorist movements Hezbollah and Hamas, he wants Britain to give up nuclear weapons and leave NATO and the EU.
For Corbyn, who at the time regarded the killing of Osama bin Laden as a real tragedy, ISIS is close to preferring the United States.
Following the model of all populist demagogues, Corbyn has, of course, miraculous anti-austerity solutions.
Things like those that Tsipras said and promised in Greece until he got rid of the real world and economic legitimacy.
The new Labour leader’s economic program includes, among other things, massive nationalizations and money printing as a solution for financing development projects and covering very generous social benefits.
Sure, some might wonder why the solution with the printing of money is not unanimously adopted worldwide, we would then have a general worldwide prosperity!
Of course, we can tax the bankers to the blood, who have become some sort of serving enemies of the left, but as has been seen so many times in the past, not only in the former communist states or in Ecuador or Venezuela, but also in France, at the beginning of the mandates of Mitterand and Hollande.
The extra amounts are quickly swallowed by the generous, uncovered promises made by populist demagogues.
As Margaret Thatcher once said, “The problem with socialism is that at some point the money of others ends up.”
Few people give Jeremy Corbyn real chances of ever becoming prime minister.
In the early 1980s another radical leftist leader, Michael Foot, who was nevertheless not as extreme in beliefs as the party’s new leader, failed deplorably in the election.
And then there was still a relatively consistent and structured working class in the classical sense of the word in Britain.
Unions were much more influential than they are now.
In the new industrial landscape, where services dominate the workforce as a whole, and extensive automation has made the industry demanding a massive high-skilled workforce, Corbyn’s rhetoric has a limited appeal.
But even from opposition, he can influence important developments that can directly affect us.
In its latest issue, the Financial Times believes that Corbyn’s election increases the chances of Brexit, namely Britain’s exit from the EU.
The new Labour leader was a consistent opponent of the country’s membership in the Union.
In the eyes of the radical left, Brussels is the agent of international capitalism and a promoter of globalization that has imposed austerity on the poor.
When you combine this kind of ideas with those expressed by the radical right, with anti-immigration rhetoric, and look at the refugee crisis shaking the foundations of the EU, you come to an explosive mix.
And not just for Britain.
But if the British decide after the referendum, which was to be held by 2017, to leave the Union, the symbolic loss of capital for the entire European project and the deep gaps created within it by the Euro and now the refugee crisis, between North and South, between East and West, leave room for the most worrying scenarios.
Especially because for a whole number of member states, London was a counterpoint to the Franco-German axis (in which, anyway, Berlin becomes the dominant actor more and more).
It is true that the British business community, the City, are strong advocates of the country’s stay in the EU.
Today’s Europe is no longer the one of the past.
There are many resentments, which increase in intensity even in these weeks.
The problem is that Brussels, we even recently had a sample in Jean-Claude Juncker’s speech, is increasingly inclined to make major decisions over the head of the vast majority of member states in consultation with only a few European powers, mainly with Germany.
And this is happening as the electoral support for anti-system, anti-immigration formations that are at the same time and eurosceptic grows dramatically across the continent.
In other words, the negative-loaded emotional climate has reached higher odds than ever before.
This is what the Financial Times concludes when it evaluates the chances of Brexit.
The pro-EU option is based on a cold calculation starting from the national interest.
If voters make a brainstorming decision, then Britain will remain in the EU.
But Corbyn’s victory reminds us of the power of emotion in current politics.
However, Eastern Europe may be significantly affected by such major developments.
Especially if, as is expected, we witness a more pronounced integration of the euro area, which will push most of the countries in the region and to the periphery of the interest and the decision-making process in Europe.
Corbyn, Tsipras and Syriza in Greece, Podemos in Spain, even Bernie Sanders in the United States feed their populist rhetoric from the frustrations accumulated in Western societies.
For economic and demographic reasons, the prosperity that has been over the past decades, the generous social benefits, can no longer continue the same in the years to come.
Under the explosive pressure of the dual crisis, the Eurozone – immigration, both provoked by hasty decisions that have taken into account only the integrationist political ambitions, not the capacity and readiness of the peoples and governments of Europe to respond to such challenges, turbulence on the continent, internal tensions in the EU will increase in intensity and can greatly affect the situation of Romania.
And it’s hard to exclude anything from the perspective of possible scenarios.
The question is whether our top political leaders are able to cope with such complicated situations.
